First, simplify the numerator and denominator: - The numerator is \( \log(n^2) - (\log n)^2 = 2 \log n - (\log n)^2 \). - Let \( x = \log n \). The numerator becomes \( -x(x - 2) \). - The denominator is \( \log n - 3 = x - 3 \). The inequality to solve is: \[ \frac{-x(x - 2)}{x - 3} \geq 0 \] Simplifying, we get: \[ \frac{x(2 - x)}{x - 3} \geq 0 \] The critical points are \( x = 0 \), \( x = 2 \), and \( x = 3 \). Analyzing the sign of the expression around these points, we find the inequality holds when: - \( x = 0 \) (i.e., \( n = 1 \)) - \( x = 2 \) (i.e., \( n = 100 \)) - \( 2 < x < 3 \) (i.e., \( 100 < n < 1000 \)) For \( n \) as a positive integer: - \( n = 1 \) - \( n = 100 \) - Integers from 101 to 999 inclusive Counting these integers: - From 101 to 999: \( 999 - 101 + 1 = 899 \) - Adding \( n = 1 \) and \( n = 100 \): \( 899 + 2 = 901 \) Thus, the number of integers \( n \) for which the expression is real is: \[ \boxed{901} \]
